  ExpressionEvaluator 28370  debugging into the JANINO libraries.                     Use one of the features, e.g. the "expression evaluator", in your program:              import org.codehaus.janino.*;  ExpressionEvaluator ee = new ExpressionEvaluator(); ee.cook("3 + 4"); System.out.println(ee.evaluate()); // Prints "7".             Compile, run, ... be happy!                           Examples                                The <a           href="https://github.com/janino-compiler/jan
  ScriptEvaluator 45447 href="#janino-as-a-script-evaluator"           aria-hidden="true">   Janino as a Script           Evaluator                                Analogously to the expression evaluator, a ScriptEvaluator API exists that compiles and processes a Java           "block", i.e. the body of a method. If a return value other than "void" is defined, then the block must           return a value of that type.                                As a special feature, it allows methods to be declared. The place and order of the method declarations is not           relevant.                     Example:           <div class="highlight 
  SimpleCompiler 50050 -a-simple-compiler" class="anchor" href="#janino-as-a-simple-compiler"           aria-hidden="true">   Janino as a Simple           Compiler                                The  SimpleCompiler  compiles a single .java file ("compilation unit").           Opposed to normal Java compilation, that compilation unit may declare  more than one  public type.                             Example:              // This is file "Hello.java", but it could have any name.  public class Foo {      public static void     main(String[] args) {         ne
